# Build System Reference

Full spec: `docs/build_system_spec.md`.

## Model

Single ELF output. Isolation is by MPU sections, not separate binaries.

```
ulipeMicroKernel/          ← kernel repo (this); only QEMU board built-in
ulipeMicroKernel_apps/     ← apps repo (sibling, optional)
<anywhere>/my_board/       ← real board chip input (external); pointed by UL_CHIP_DIR
build/                     ← generated artefacts (never committed)
```

Real board chip inputs (memory.ld, bmhd.ld.in) live OUTSIDE the kernel repo.
Only `boards/qemu_tc27x/` is shipped with the kernel — it is the CI platform.

## App Discovery

Top-level `CMakeLists.txt` checks for sibling at configure time:

```cmake
set(UL_APPS_DIR "${CMAKE_SOURCE_DIR}/../ulipeMicroKernel_apps" CACHE PATH "")
if(EXISTS "${UL_APPS_DIR}/CMakeLists.txt")
    add_subdirectory(${UL_APPS_DIR} _apps)
else()
    # kernel-only: stub root_thread linked in from stub/root_thread_stub.c
endif()
```

Override: `-DUL_APPS_DIR=/path/to/apps`

## Chip Selection

```bash
cmake -B build -DUL_CHIP_DIR=boards/qemu_tc27x   # QEMU
cmake -B build -DUL_CHIP_DIR=boards/tc27x         # real HW
```

`UL_CHIP_DIR` must point to a directory with `memory.ld` (chip input Layer 3,
see linker-spec rule and `docs/linker_spec.md §9`).

## CMake API (defined in cmake/linker_api.cmake)

```cmake
ul_add_app(NAME <n> SOURCES <f…> DOMAIN <d> STACK <bytes> PRIV DRIVER|USER)
ul_add_domain(NAME <n> PERMS "<expr>" SHARED TRUE|FALSE)
ul_set_root_thread(SOURCE <file>)   # exactly one per build
ul_generate_linker_script()         # call after all ul_add_* calls
```

`ul_add_app` compiles sources with `-DUL_APP_NAME=<name>` → functions land in
`.text.<name>.*` sections → captured by `app_code.ld.in` snippet.

## Build Flow

```
cmake configure:
  linker_api.cmake loaded
  sibling / UL_APPS_DIR checked → ul_add_app/domain/root_thread calls
  ul_generate_linker_script() → PRE_LINK: generate_ld.py → build/generated.ld

cmake build:
  compile kernel, arch, apps, root_thread
  [PRE_LINK] generate_ld.py
  link ulipe.elf -T build/generated.ld
```

## Kernel Configuration (§9)

Exactly 5 symbols — CMake cache variables, no Kconfig, no separate config file:

```cmake
-DUL_CONFIG_MAX_THREADS=32       # TCB pool size
-DUL_CONFIG_MAX_ENDPOINTS=64     # IPC endpoint pool
-DUL_CONFIG_MAX_NOTIFS=32        # notification object pool
-DUL_CONFIG_MAX_IRQ_BINDINGS=16  # SRPN→notif binding table
-DUL_CONFIG_TICK_HZ=1000         # scheduler tick rate
```

`configure_file(cmake/config.h.in ${CMAKE_BINARY_DIR}/include/ul/config.h)`

The header is internal to the kernel. User code does not include it.
Everything else is either a hardware constant (arch_config.h), a memory-sizing
parameter (memory.ld), or a userspace policy decision.

## Root Thread Contract

Apps provide exactly one:
```c
void ul_root_thread(const ul_boot_info_t *info);
```
Kernel-only builds use `stub/root_thread_stub.c` (calls `ul_thread_exit()`).

## ul_board_init — Optional Chip Setup Callback

```c
/* stub/board_init_stub.c — weak no-op; user overrides with strong symbol */
__attribute__((weak)) void ul_board_init(void) {}
```

Runs as the FIRST C function in the system, before .data copy, before any kernel
API. Intended for PLL, flash wait states, external RAM. No CMake registration —
just define `ul_board_init()` anywhere in the link and the strong symbol wins.

**Constraints:** no .data vars, no ul_* API, no interrupt enable, must return.

Boot sequence:
```
_start → ul_board_init() → .data copy → .bss zero → ul_arch_init() → ul_kernel_main()
```

When a dedicated bootloader is used, leave `ul_board_init()` as the no-op stub.
